Sharing this story since @0x_b1 revealed his identity.

And I feel it's a small chapter in the crypto chronicles.

Finally, the idea that transparency is a killer feature of blockchains.

Every Smart Money wallet is potentially a masterclass. You can learn a ton by seeing what the best traders and investors do.

Secondly, @0x_b1 embodies the concept of *on-chain identity*.

And people should be able to communicate from their on-chain identity.

This is why we built Nansen Connect - which allows for e2e encrypted DMs between wallets: https://t.co/k4l3xoXfuD

Firstly, the concept of "Smart Money".

When we shipped our algos that classify wallets as Smart Money, @0x_b1 was one of the wallets that got tagged.

They also got a few other cool labels (... or are they badges?) https://t.co/MmS3t7jJd1

I still think @0x_b1 is an incredibly fascinating experiment and concept.

His appearance strengthened two of my core beliefs that also shaped Nansen as a product.

As many of us know, from there @0x_b1 quickly became a top on-chain influencer.

A true degen among degens.

He never said anything about who this wallet was - nor did I ask.

It was a fun meeting, but my poor follow-up meant we didn't speak again.

But then a few days later I came across this: https://t.co/dbaWBaC4aO

I plug it in and see what appears to be an incredibly active DeFi wallet.

Here it is btw: https://t.co/68kNFzGwZR

(screenshots below are from a snapshot today) https://t.co/YoDYbYMmZZ

I asked: any address you want to have a look at?

He said - try this:

0xb1adceddb2941033a090dd166a462fe1c2029484

The Wallet Profiler - today one of Nansen's most popular features - allows you to plug in an address, and you get insights about that wallet.

Things like:
- Counterparties of the wallet
- Activity patterns
- Tokens traded
- Related wallets
etc

When I demo Nansen, there's no script.

We just look at whatever's happening on the screen, because there's always something interesting to dig into.

But this time I had built a new feature: the Wallet Profiler. https://t.co/PHX0TDdXk0

Disclaimer: I‚Äôm a random person on Twitter. This is not financial advice. I have no credentials except my profile pic is a penguin.

In summary:

I expect the ‚Äúalways up‚Äù trend of property prices to meet its end in our lifetime - possibly sooner than most think.

5) Mobility

Coming generations will move around more, which means owning a home is less appealing (except for rental income).

Homeowners age is at ATH by the way. https://t.co/TrE6GxJ8Kk

4) cont.

This is changing.

You can already collateralize crypto. For many reasons it‚Äôs a vastly superior asset to use as collateral, and it‚Äôll only get better.

Over time this means the RE advantage of leverage faces more competition. (Similar to the 1st point.)

4) Leverage

Buying a home has been the only way to get cheap leverage on an investment.

If you have $100k in savings, banks can offer (at least) $400k in a mortgage, giving you 5x leverage at ultra-low interest rates.

3) Population growth

The ‚Äúalways up‚Äù mindset of property prices has been accompanied by an insane population growth.

This will slow down over the next decades.

Less people growth, less growth in demand for housing (ceteris paribus). https://t.co/OfhpDXgMUD

2) Politics

With rising inequality, RE ownership will likely get more concentrated.

If >50% rent (rather than own), politicians will pander to their wishes.

Pro-tenant policies will make it less attractive to own property.

1) Options

Our parents‚Äô generation had one asset class to invest in: their home.

Coming generations will have a lot more options available to them. Stocks are much more available now, and crypto + metaverse assets will add tons of new assets.

So RE has a lot more competition.

I think real estate will have been a poor investment 20y+ from now.

If you found this interesting, consider joining Nansen as Research Analyst so you can pioneer the study of markets and humans using on-chain data: https://t.co/kwQPFFIUfn

Two closing remarks:
1) someone should do an actual paper on this effect
2) I'm shocked we don't have more economists and sociologists flocking to crypto to study markets and humans. We literally have better data than any other field!

But I would argue it's more likely that 2) is probably the main driver.

We tend to overestimate the chances that we'll get a rare piece.

In fact, humans often feel like longshot events are more likely than they actually are - see: https://t.co/cuzcoA9kju

It seems like for 1) to be true, NFT collections have to consistently disappoint.

Maybe a bit like ICOs did after 2017. https://t.co/F4cg7H4TpV

I can think of two immediate explanations:
1) people are disappointed with the art/traits
2) people were overly optimistic about their chances to receive a rare item

The curious thing is that - anecdotally - it seems like the total market cap tends to go down after trait reveals.

Example with @MekaVerse again: https://t.co/gxZyi5Eo53

This makes perfect sense!

By definition, *most items are not rare*, so it's expected to see most pieces become less valuable after a trait reveal.

But it's one reason why you'll see a lot of people disappointed after a trait reveal.

After a trait reveal, the market cap shifts to become concentrated towards rare pieces. Conversely, less rare pieces will lose value.

Here you see this happening with @MekaVerse: https://t.co/Qt9oJB52ov

Consider an NFT collection of 10,000 items priced at 1 ETH each, then its market cap is 10,000 ETH.

Before a trait reveal, each item should be priced the same.

(Assuming the market only bases price on traits, and ignoring popular IDs like #1 and #69.)

Postulating the existence of a lottery premium of NFT trait reveals. Aka the NFT Hopium Effect.

Trait reveals shouldn't impact the total market cap of an NFT collection (on average). But they do!

Why?

So an information service that helps you spot inefficiencies and opportunities is ‚Ä¶ very valuable!

And I think that‚Äôs why our customers love @nansen_ai 

Try it out and see what you think: https://t.co/BtCBIRLjGi

ü§ë Crypto is insanely fragmented and fast-moving.

Even those of us who work full-time in the industry struggle to keep up.

This creates dislocations and inefficiencies all over the place (good).

And still, you can execute transactions in seconds at low costs (also good!).

üìà Publicly traded stocks are relatively low-cost to trade (good). But it‚Äôs extremely hard to find inefficiencies (bad).

So an information service that helps you spot opportunities is ‚Ä¶ not really easy to build at all!

üè° Real estate is inefficient (good for investors), but transaction costs are high (bad).

I could find mispriced properties in Vietnam, but the cost to act on the opportunity is high.

So an information service that helps me spot RE opportunities is not that valuable.

ü§îWhy is the value of information so high in crypto?

It‚Äôs simple:
inefficient market + low tx costs

2) You price out the high-risk customers.

This means they'll go to your competitor where they'll collect a disproportionate amount of claims (and your competitor will have incorrectly modeled it).

More claims for your competitor; less premiums.

1) You can offer lower premiums to low-risk customers.

This means you attract the good customers from your competitors.

These customers won't collect much claims (and you will have accurately priced it).

More premiums for you; less claims.

Insurance is unbelievably boring from the consumer's perspective.

BUT the game theory of insurance companies from the business perspective is really interesting.

Yet most companies end up being stuck in analysis paralysis nonetheless.

When I'm asked to advise on AI/ML projects, there's almost always some fancy idea for the first model.

90% of the time my advice is the same:

1. Figure out what metric you want to move
2. Start with a really dumb model
3. Try it
4. Evaluate on metric vs a baseline
5. Iterate

5. parameters set by KyberDAO

What's the current status and future of HKDai?

HKDai is currently in its very first iteration, which means it only supports the bare minimum: deposits/withdraws + basic ERC20 token functionality.
When implemented correctly, this means the HKDai-Dai peg is unbreakable.

Withdraw is the opposite operation: it lets you withdraw Dai from the smart contract. You must return 7.8 HKDai for every 1 Dai you want to withdraw. The HKDai you return are taken out of circulation.
Deposit lets you deposit Dai into the smart contract. You receive exactly 7.8 HKDai for every 1 Dai you deposit. These 7.8 HKDai are minted at the time of your deposit.

How does HKDai work?

HKDai in its current form is based on a simple smart contract. The main two features of the contract (in addition to standard ERC20 functions) are: deposit and withdraw.

Specifically, HKDai:
- requires no bank account - only an Ethereum wallet
- can be sent to anyone, anywhere in the world, within seconds
- has a stable value, as it is pegged to Dai at a constant rate of exactly 7.8 : 1
- cannot be blocked or intercepted by any intermediaries

But let's take a step back - why HKDai?

HKDai gives the people of Hong Kong a familiar currency in a digital form, with the benefits of the Ethereum ecosystem.
This means that you can always redeem your HKDai for Dai at a rate of exactly 7.8 HKDai per 1 Dai. This is guaranteed via an open-source smart contract issued on the Ethereum blockchain.

While the HKD is pegged by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) intervening in markets at certain price points (sell HKD at HK$7.75; buy HKD at HK$7.85), HKDai is 100% collateralized by Dai.

As you probably know, Dai is pegged to the USD.

What is HKDai?

HKDai is a cryptocurrency which - similarly to the Hong Kong Dollar (HKD) - is soft-pegged to the US Dollar (USD) at a rate of 7.8 HKDai to 1 USD.
